body:
I can add some more information on this. I could also reproduce it on an LG G3.

Upon resuming, `playAnimation(true)` will be called (on LottieDrawable).
There we have the following code:
```
if (setStartTime) {
  animator.setCurrentPlayTime((long) (progress * animator.getDuration()));
}
animator.start();
```

Switching the order of these instructions would potentially fix the problem. However, the `AnimatorUpdateListener` is called with `0.0f` as soon as we call `animator.start()`, which happens before we set the current play time.

```
animator.addUpdateListener(new ValueAnimator.AnimatorUpdateListener() {
      @Override public void onAnimationUpdate(ValueAnimator animation) {
        if (systemAnimationsAreDisabled) {
          animator.cancel();
          setProgress(1f);
        } else {
      ----> setProgress((float) animation.getAnimatedValue());
        }
      }
    });
```

This will set the progress and when the `setCurrentPlayTime` finally runs, the progress will already be at `0.0f`.

In my app, I fixed the problem by saving the progress before calling resume and setting it myself.
```
    void resumeAnimation() {
        float progress = animationView.getProgress();
        animationView.resumeAnimation();

        ValueAnimator animator = getAnimator();
        if (animator != null) {
            animator.setCurrentPlayTime((long) (progress * animator.getDuration()));
        }
    }
```

This is not ideal as `getAnimator()` uses reflection.

Update, we have figured out a workaround for the issue....

```
(LottieAnimationView) view;
view.setSpeed((BigDecimal.valueOf(SECONDS_IN_MINUTE_FLOAT)
        .divide(BigDecimal.valueOf(totalStateSeconds), 
                MathContext.DECIMAL128)).floatValue());
view.setProgress(totalStateSeconds);
view.playAnimation();
view.pauseAnimation();
view.resumeAnimation();
```

Definitely not ideal! but it works for us for now.
